 given context and agreed upon by the community. It is this concept that sets mathematics apart from other disciplines and distinguishes it as the prototype of a deductive science. Proofs thus are utterly relevant for research, teaching and communication in mathematics and of particular interest for the philosophy of mathematics. In computer science, moreover, proofs have proved to be a rich source for already certified algorithms. This book provides the reader with a collection of articles covering relevant current research topics circled around the concept 'proof'. It tries to give due consideration to the depth and breadth of the subject by discussing its philosophical and methodological aspects, addressing foundational issues induced by Hilbert's Programme and the benefits of the arising formal notions of proof, without neglecting reasoning in natural language proofs and applications in computer science such as program extraction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLogic, Symbolic and mathematical. 0aMathematics. 0aProof theory. 4aMathematische Logik. 4aPhilosophie der Mathematik. 4aTheoretische Informatik. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Epistemology.2bisacsh  aMathematical Logic.  aPhilosophy of Mathematics.  aTheoretical Computer Science.1 aAfshari, Bahareh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenini, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Ulrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBridges, Douglas S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchholtz, Ulrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoquand, Thierry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDošen, Kosta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel